REST API HTTP Status Codes Guide

REST APIs use HTTP status codes to indicate the result of a client’s request.

Status Code Categories

1xx : Informational (request received, processing continues)
2xx : Success
3xx : Redirection (further action needed)
4xx : Client-side errors
5xx : Server-side errors

---

1xx — Informational

Indicates the request has been received and is still being processed.

100 Continue
The server received request headers and expects the body.
Example: Uploading a large file — server tells client to continue sending data.

101 Switching Protocols
Server switches protocol based on client request.
Example: Upgrading HTTP connection to WebSocket for real-time chat.

102 Processing (WebDAV)
Request is being processed, no response yet.
Example: Bulk file operation like copying thousands of files.

103 Early Hints
Hints to preload resources before full response.
Example: Browser starts loading CSS/JS before full page is received.

---

2xx — Success

Request was successfully received and processed.

200 OK
Request succeeded.
Example: GET /users/123 returns user data.

201 Created
New resource created.
Example: POST /users creates a new user.

202 Accepted
Request accepted but processing is not complete.
Example: Report generation running in background.

203 Non-Authoritative Information
Response from cached or third-party source.
Example: Proxy returns cached API response.

204 No Content
Request succeeded, no response body.
Example: DELETE /posts/45 removes a post successfully.

205 Reset Content
Client should reset UI/form.
Example: Form submission completed and UI should clear fields.

---

3xx — Redirection

Further action required to complete request.

300 Multiple Choices
Multiple response options available.
Example: API provides JSON or XML options.

301 Moved Permanently
Resource permanently moved.
Example: /api/v1/users moved to /api/v2/users.

302 Found (Temporary Redirect)
Resource temporarily moved.
Example: Redirect after login to dashboard.

303 See Other
Response available via different URI using GET.
Example: Redirect to confirmation page after form submission.

305 Use Proxy
Request must go through proxy.
Example: Company network requires proxy for API access.

---

4xx — Client Errors

Error caused by client-side issues.

400 Bad Request
Invalid request syntax.
Example: Missing required fields in request body.

401 Unauthorized
Authentication required or failed.
Example: Accessing API without token.

402 Payment Required
Reserved for payment-based APIs.
Example: Premium API requires subscription.

403 Forbidden
Client lacks permission.
Example: User trying to delete another user's data.

404 Not Found
Resource not found.
Example: Requesting a non-existent product.

---

5xx — Server Errors

Server failed to process a valid request.

500 Internal Server Error
Generic server failure.
Example: Database crash during request.

501 Not Implemented
Method not supported.
Example: Using unsupported HTTP method like PATCH.

502 Bad Gateway
Invalid response from upstream server.
Example: API gateway gets corrupted response.

503 Service Unavailable
Server unavailable or overloaded.
Example: Server under maintenance.

504 Gateway Timeout
Upstream server timeout.
Example: Dependent service takes too long to respond.

505 HTTP Version Not Supported
HTTP version not supported.
Example: Client uses unsupported HTTP version.

---

Summary

1xx → Request in progress
2xx → Success
3xx → Redirection
4xx → Client error
5xx → Server error

